The Zamfara State House of Assembly has concluded arrangement to investigate the alleged diversion of N1.258bn given to 2,516 primary health care centres in the state for the purchase of drugs. About N610,000 was released to each of the 2516 PHCs in the state by National Basic Health Care Provision Funds to augment their urgent health care needs, but only N276,760 was given to them,  while N1. 258bn was allegedly diverted. In a statement, the Director General Press Affairs and Public Relations of the Assembly, Alhaji Mustafa Jafaru, said, the lawmakers had passed a resolution to investigate the alleged illegal diversion of the funds. Jafaru said the decision to investigate the funds was made following a matters of urgent public importance raised during plenary by the House Leader, Faruk Dosara. The statement quoted Dosara as saying, “The money was released by the National basic Health Care Provision Fund to augment the urgent health care needs of the primary health centres of the country, Zamfara State inclusive.” He alleged that, the sum of N500,000 was cornered to a different account domicile in Drugs and Consumables Management Agency. The Speaker of the House, Nasiru Magarya, mandated the House Committee on Health and Human Medicine under to investigate the matter and submit its findings to the House in the next one month. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com